Explanation:

I inspected the controller, request validation, resource transformation, model, and routes to determine how the PUT /v1/posts/{post} endpoint behaves and what inputs/outputs it supports.

Key findings used to construct the OpenAPI Operation object:
- Route: routes/api.php registers posts update inside a middleware group requiring authentication ('auth:sanctum', 'verified'), so the operation requires authenticated access.
- Controller method: PostController::update(PostsRequest $request, Post $post) updates the Post model and returns a PostResource (JSON representation of the updated post).
- Request validation (PostsRequest) enforces these fields: title (required), content (required), posted_at (required date), author_id (required integer referencing users), thumbnail_id (nullable integer referencing media). The controller only uses the subset: title, content, posted_at, author_id, thumbnail_id.
- Response shape (PostResource) returns JSON with: id, title, slug, content, posted_at (ISO 8601), author_id, comments_count, thumbnail_url, thumb_thumbnail_url. posted_at in resource is produced as ISO8601 string.
- Path parameter {post} is resolved by route model binding; for API requests the model uses the numeric id as route key, so the path parameter is an integer id.

Based on the above, the Operation object describes:
- summary, description, tags, and operationId for identification.
- a path parameter "post" (integer, required).
- requestBody for application/json with the validated fields (title, content, posted_at, author_id required; thumbnail_id nullable).
- responses including 200 (returns the Post resource JSON). I also include common error responses that are implied by the route/controller behavior: 401 Unauthorized (authentication required), 403 Forbidden (authorization via $this->authorize), and 422 Unprocessable Entity (validation errors).

